                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I have played Everquest since beta, and have played our class through many, many changes.  I've been charming since level 12, long before Kunark ever came out.  In my opinion, we are the most difficult class in the game to balance.
<br />

<br />
The real source of this problem, is not that charm was/is overpowered, although that is definately a symptom; many people seem to fail to see beyond that. The real problem is that eq has a basic, fundemental flaw.  This flaw is that a mob of a given level is more powerful than a player of the same level. 
<br />

<br />
If a level 65 warrior mob was a fair match for a level 65 warrior player, then charm wouldn't even be an issue.
<br />

<br />
This was done to create "challenge".  Mobs are very dumb, which is why we have froglok wizards wielding rapiers and hitting for over a hundred of points of damage at level 40 (while I can't wield a rapier, at level 65 with good gear I can now melee for over a hundred points of damage too).  If mobs were smart, they would protect each other.  They would use crowd control on us, they would taunt us and force our targets to switch away from their healers.  They would not be fooled by some big warrior's attempt to insult them, they would go after that weakling in a robe, or that healer that they'd know is the real threat.
<br />

<br />
But, rather than having mobs work together, or smarter, the game is tuned for taking a single group (6 people) vs a single mob.  The mobs come in clusters, but they don't really work together.  What we do, is apply the maximum force to the minimum area and call it "control". 
<br />

<br />
--
<br />

<br />
Over time, the game has advanced, players progress, new expansions get released.  Bigger and better gear becomes available to the players.  In order to maintain this sense of "challenge", mobs must also be scaled up accordingly.  In order to account for the extra difficulty (even tho mobs may be of the same level), experience modifiers are adjusted.
<br />

<br />
It is always a tricky balancing act.  Players get better weapons, and do more dps, so mobs get more hitpoints as to not be trivial.  Players get more hitpoints, and mobs get higher dps.
<br />

<br />
What charm does, is to use your opponents' strength against them.  It takes those newly scaled up mobs and uses them to devestate other scaled up mobs.  The problem, is that this scaling of dps vs hitpoints for players vs mobs is not even.  The further along this path we went, the faster mobs have been able to kill themselves; And thus, the more powerful charm became.
<br />

<br />
Rather than trying to fix alot of the core problems with the game, with PoP, SoE raised the level of the game to another level.  Each level from 61 - 65 had significantly more of an impact than previous levels, and basically, older content was reduced in importance.   While it certainly was a valid strategy, it still doesn't fix the core issues.  With PoP, charm gained a huge jump in power, because the mobs did too.
<br />

<br />
Then with LDoN, the attempt was to simply reduce the number of charmable targets so enchanters would keep their pet, making them a precious resource.
<br />

<br />
With GoD, they simply made flagged most mobs uncharmable. (KT, Qvic?), but they did leave us charmable mobs for the initial content, (sewers using LDoN-style restrictions), with tipt and vxed being left in its pure form, and that is often where charm is considered most "unbalancing".
<br />

<br />
Now, in OoW, they're looking for yet another way to patch over this flaw.  Mobs don't hit as hard as they did in GoD, or even a good portion of PoP, for that matter.  But still, they're trying to overcome the core problem of mob hp/dps balance.   
<br />

<br />
--
<br />

<br />
I greatly enjoy a clever challenge, but I really don't like one that is a only challenge because I'm at a disadvantage.  That just doesn't appeal to me at all.  The current dps cap for charmed mobs smells alot more like the latter than the former.  
<br />

<br />
I'm not saying our class is ruined, or crying that I can't exp faster than necros.  We've been through worse.  I'd honestly like to have Sony share their discussions about balancing classes with us, rather than simply taking our imput (or not, never really do get comments to know if they even hear us).  I want Sony's input.  I want them to ask us about ideas that they have.  I want to know what *they* see as a problem.  I would have loved to have seen a "Hey guys, we think charm is having a bad effect on the game, here are some examples...  We are considering the following options...  What comments or other ideas do you have?". 
<br />
I want communication to go both ways.  I want eq to prosper and to continually improve.  I'm sure that SoE's goals must be similiar.
<br />

<br />
--
<br />

<br />
Personally, I think that the solution lies in having mobs that can dual wield, already doing so (alot of mobs in OoW seem to do this already) rather than being tuned without it, and just waiting for someone else to equip them.  I could also see making charm and haste exclusive (1% slow is fine).  
<br />

<br />
If a mob has 35k hitpoints, and can do 35k damage in 1 minute, then thats what charm should be able to add to a group.  These could even be done retro-actively, and while it would weaken charm, it would still be worth the risk to use (even if just barely).
<br />

<br />
I've noticed that the AI has gotten better over the years, mobs now dispel mezed allies, etc.  I think they should do the same to charmed allies, or at least recognize them as former allies.  That would definately increase the risk.  Perhaps mobs using memory blur on charmed mobs (or even other pets) to get them to stop attacking.  Maybe just mezing them, rooting, etc.
<br />

<br />
--
<br />

<br />
Regardless of wether or not decisions get made as I would make them, I'd still like to see proactive changes to the real issues rather than seeing knee-jerk reactions to the current symptoms.  You can only plug so many holes in a boat before it'll sink. I'd rather fix the boat than find more plugs.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=378985" target="_blank" class="postlink">Master Tashim</a>
<br />
<a href="http://www.botsguild.org/" target="_blank" class="postlink">Brotherhood of the Spider</a>, <a href="http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency" target="_blank" class="postlink">The Rathe</a>
<br />

<br />
