                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">WHY DOES NOBODY UNDERSTAND THE 33% RULE?!</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Many people see your pet as a group wipe waiting to happen that also diminishes thier visible per-unit experience.
<br />

<br />
IMHO, the base trouble is that few groups perform at thier capacity.  They pull slowly, don't stack mobs,  and generally mess around between kills.   When the members are looking at thier exp bar,  all they see is 3% or 4% per mob.  They can measure that they are going to kill a mob every 2 minutes regardless, because that's how long it takes to go get one.
<br />

<br />
So, many people are out there min-maxing thier per-kill instead of thier per-time.  High DPS charmpets and the exp nerf wonk that plan totally, but the obvious speed of kill allows them to feel good about sparing a player's dps to pull instead of fight.  People get upset about your bringing along a sub-damage charmpet because its underwhelming dps doesn't visibly speed things up while visibly decreasing per-kill experience over a 5 to 10 mob sample.
<br />

<br />
I agree that it's not the smartest point of view, and I think it's going to be a real social problem in OOW with dangerous, low damage charmpets.
<br />

<br />
However, it's a sensible position to take if you've been beaten for 65 levels for not being overly cautious.  I think a lot of casual players are in that category, and if OOW turns out to be the casual heaven I expeect it to be, this will really hurt enchanters in OOW.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
